data.title: Life story: Napolean's secret weapon - Jos√©phine Bonaparte
data.meta_description: She was the wife of one of the world's most famous empire builders, but Josephine Bonaparte was a cunning tactician in her own right, says author and historian Kate Williams
data.text:
She was the wife of one of the world‚Äôs most famous empire builders, but Josephine Bonaparte was a cunning tactician in her own right, says author and historian Kate Williams

S Fran√ßois G√©rard portrait of Jos√©phine

Paris, 1795. Antique chandeliers glitter over tables groaning with food. Napoleon Bonaparte, a gauche young general, arrives at a gala dinner at a palace once occupied by Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette. The government wants him to be its military errand boy, so it greets him with its trump card: Jos√©phine de Beauharnais, the most glamorous and alluring woman in Paris.

Then 32, Jos√©phine, a widow, was a legendary seductress. Mistress to Paul Barras, France‚Äôs most powerful politician, she was a style icon and post-revolutionary heroine, having narrowly avoided the guillotine. She was impoverished, with a mouthful of black teeth, but was versed in every art of love. At her best in the candlelight, her low-cut gown clinging to her, she slipped into a chair next to Napoleon, fluttering her eyelashes as she asked about his military victories.

Alexandre de Beauharnais

The 26-year-old general, ugly, graceless and inexperienced with women, was totally intoxicated. By the end of the evening he was, he confessed, ‚Äòpassionately in love‚Äô. One of the greatest love affairs in history had begun.

More than five years ago, I set off to Paris to research Jos√©phine‚Äôs life. As I read her letters, I was fascinated by how different she was from the popular image of a subservient, decorative featherbrain. In fact, she presented herself as excessively feminine to trick people into underestimating her, and it was a successful strategy. She was highly intelligent and ambitious for power, an aspiration she gained through the most transformative experience of her life ‚Äì her period in prison.

Napoleon was fascinated by Jos√©phine because she seemed so very French, but she was an outsider like him (he was born in Corsica and mocked for it): a Martinique girl from a down-at-heel family, who had clawed her way up with her skills of flattery and intrigue. She had kept up an image of gentility on a few pennies, sold her virtue to the highest bidder, fought to survive ‚Äì all behind a mask of charming serenity. When she met Napoleon, she was at the height of her influence. She saw him as an easy target.

Until the fateful dinner with Jos√©phine in 1795, Napoleon had been wandering Paris, dazzled by fashionable women and feeling excluded from society. He couldn‚Äôt believe his luck meeting Mme de Beauharnais. She was beautiful, glamorous, eager to praise him ‚Äì and she had access to the most influential people in France. Most of all, he was impressed by how she had, from inauspicious beginnings, transformed herself into the darling of Paris. He wanted to learn how she had done it.

Napoleon bombarded Jos√©phine with letters, and soon she was his lover. ‚ÄòYour image gives me no rest,‚Äô he wrote, offering her a thousand kisses. He never said ‚ÄòNot tonight, Jos√©phine‚Äô, the phrase we most associate with them. In reality, he was always desperate for her body. ‚ÄòI am coming home,‚Äô he once wrote to her. ‚ÄòDon‚Äôt wash.‚Äô As she later said, ‚ÄòHe does not love me, he worships me. I think he will go mad.‚Äô

Less than a year after they first met, Jos√©phine was waiting in her prettiest dress at the town hall of Paris‚Äôs second municipal district for Napoleon to arrive and marry her. He bounded up the stairs, four hours late because he had been planning his invasion of Italy (he made it up to her by knocking four years off her age on the marriage certificate).

With this fellow outsider as his wife, he aimed to conquer the world.

As a little girl, Jos√©phine had been told by a fortune teller that she would be queen of France. But her childhood was far from that of the future wife of a king. Marie Jos√®phe Rose Tascher de La Pagerie was born in 1763 into a poor plantation family in Martinique, the first of three daughters for her gambling-addict father. As a child she ran wild under the Caribbean sun.

An Antoine-Jean Gros painting of Napoleon

At 16, she was packed off to an aunt in Paris for an arranged marriage with a young aristocrat, Alexandre de Beauharnais. He loathed her, calling her plump and unsophisticated, and the birth of a son and daughter did not win him over ‚Äì she was barely 20 when he told her the marriage was over and sent her and the children to live in a convent.

Jos√©phine was not easily beaten. She begged the other abandoned wives there for tips on beauty and dress. She learned the arts of a true Parisienne ‚Äì dress, grace and seductive speech. She painted her face with white make-up, daubed her cheeks with rouge and painted the lids of her exotic amber eyes with dusky coal powder. When Alexandre finally bowed to family pressure and let her out after just over a year, she had become a truly beautiful woman. Her husband remained immune to her charms, but other men flocked to pay her bills, and she lived off their favours.

Jos√©phine was finally free to live as she wished. But in 1794, the revolutionary mob who had executed Louis and Marie Antoinette were still rounding up aristocrats under the Terror. They arrested Alexandre as a traitor, and shortly afterwards, Jos√©phine, as his wife, was sent to Les Carmes, the most brutal prison in Paris.

Les Carmes was a truly dreadful place. Women waited in their flimsy linen underdresses for the guillotine, their hair cut short in expectation of the blade. Jos√©phine prayed; she seduced a general who she hoped might protect her ‚Äì but it all seemed hopeless. Alexandre was tried and executed. She knew she was next.

Part of The Consecration of the Emperor Napoleon and the Coronation of Empress Jos√©phine by Jacques-Louis David.

Then, on the day before her trial, the government was deposed, and the new men in charge immediately halted the executions. Jos√©phine had escaped by the skin of her teeth ‚Äì and she was changed for ever. She would never let herself be vulnerable again. She had been told she would be queen of France; now she was determined to make it happen.

Jos√©phine befriended the flamboyant socialite Th√©r√©sa Tallien. Another former prisoner, Th√©r√©sa was the mistress, later wife, of a politician, and France‚Äôs darling. She took Jos√©phine to parties and showed her off as a beauty. Dubbed the Merveilleuses, Th√©r√©sa, Jos√©phine and their friends became stars. ‚ÄòAn event!‚Äô ran one headline. ‚ÄòChange in the style of hairdressing of Mesdames Beauharnais and Tallien.‚Äô

Parisians were hungry to celebrate their survival. Everyone wanted to attend the Bals des Victimes where women wore red ribbons around their necks as a symbol of the guillotine. The new fashion was the ‚Äòprison look‚Äô: short hair and, in tribute to the prisoners‚Äô underdresses, tiny, white, diaphanous gowns. Jos√©phine‚Äôs were practically see-through. She wanted to shock and win fame, and after the horrors of Les Carmes, she did not care what people thought. She and Th√©r√©sa dampened their gowns with perfume to make them cling to their curves.

Jos√©phine had her sights set on one man: Paul Barras, impossibly wealthy and the de facto governor of France. With beautiful Th√©r√©sa as her back-up, she seduced him easily. Barras gave her a magnificent home and loved her for her grace, skills as a hostess and indulgence of his debauched desires; for his political dinners turned into orgies when the clock struck 12. Jos√©phine danced nearly naked, while Th√©r√©sa dipped her breast into Barras‚Äôs glass of champagne.

By 1795, Jos√©phine was over 30, and she knew Barras was tiring of her. She needed security, preferably a husband. When her lover asked her to sit next to Napoleon, she used all her charms to win him.

Society was shocked by its favourite girl stepping out with a sallow-faced soldier without money or connections, but Jos√©phine saw his potential. She was right. In the ten years that followed their marriage, Napoleon tricked and manoeuvred, ousting Barras and making himself consul and then, in 1804, emperor of France.

All the while, Jos√©phine was Napoleon‚Äôs helpmate, gaining the trust of the various parties that he needed for his aims. He could not have triumphed without her. Where he was gruff and often aggressive, she was gentle, smoothing over situations at court and lulling the elite into believing he would protect them.

French emperor Napoleon Bonaparte's (1769 -1821) farewell to wife Josephine.

Jos√©phine was an actress, her greatest role that of the beautiful consort, adorned in diamonds and fabulous gowns, the proof of Napoleon‚Äôs power. She had more ladies-in-waiting than Marie Antoinette; more jewels than any queen has ever possessed, before or since. One gown was covered entirely in rose petals, another in hundreds of diamond-tipped toucan feathers. She complained to a friend that she was little more than a ‚Äòbejewelled slave‚Äô, though she was careful to seem delighted by the grandeur when her husband was around.

But Napoleon needed an heir, and Jos√©phine, despite numerous visits to doctors, was unable to conceive. In 1809, she turned 46, and Napoleon gave in to his ministers‚Äô pleas. He sat down to dinner with her and told her he must divorce her in order to have a son with another wife.

Marie Louise and the King of Rome, a portrait of Napoleon's second wife and their son by Fran√ßois G√©rard

Jos√©phine‚Äôs screams could be heard across the palace. That night, she went to him to try to win him back. ‚ÄòGo, Jos√©phine,‚Äô he said, ‚ÄòI will always be your friend.‚Äô

Jos√©phine retreated to their beautiful home outside Paris, Malmaison. She tended her garden and watched her husband marry Marie Louise of Austria and have a longed-for son. She smiled and threw celebratory balls, hiding her tears.

But without Jos√©phine by his side, Napoleon‚Äôs luck ran out. His invasion of Russia in 1812 was a terrible failure. The dictator who had terrorised Europe was vulnerable, and by early 1814, the British and Russians were marching on Paris. Napoleon was captured and imprisoned.

Jos√©phine remained devoted to her former husband and was broken by his imprisonment. Just over a month later, in late May, she caught a chill walking in the gardens. A few days after that, on the day she was due to open a ball, she died. Without Napoleon, she had no spirit to live.

I have scoured archives, read thousands of letters, and investigated the cruel diaries of her enemies. Jos√©phine‚Äôs life is a gripping story: at a time when women had little power, she seized what she could. Napoleon needed Jos√©phine beside him to secure his victories over the French people. She was no lightweight, but a woman of intelligence, determination and a capacity to love. When Napoleon died in exile seven years later, the last word he uttered was ‚ÄòJos√©phine‚Äô.
